<HEADLINE>
<P>
HOCKEY STANLEY CUP PLAYOFFS; 
</P>
<P>
BRUINS BEAT CANADIENS, 6-3, NEAR SWEEP 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
It hasn't happened in 61 years, but the Boston Bruins are on the verge of 
sweeping the Montreal Canadiens in the NHL playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
The Bruins, with two goals from John Carter, beat the Canadiens, 6-3, Monday 
night at Montreal to take a 3-0 lead in their best-of-seven Adams Division 
championship series. 
</P>
<P>
The Bruins' only other sweep of the Canadiens was in a best-of-five series in 
1929, their teams' initial playoff meeting. The Bruins can advance to the Wales 
Conference final with a victory at Montreal Wednesday night. 
</P>
<P>
"We weren't that sure about (winning) it before tonight, but we are now," 
Carter said. 
</P>
<P>
Only two teams in NHL playoff history, the Toronto Maple Leafs in 1942 and the 
New York Islanders in 1975, have rebounded from 3-0 deficits to win. 
</P>
<P>
"It's been done in the past, not often, but what better place to start than 
with the 20 guys in this room," Montreal center Brian Skrudland said. "We've 
just got to go out and win the next game and take it from there." 
</P>
<P>
Carter broke a 2-2 tie at 5:30 of the second period when he beat Patrick Roy 
with a high wrist shot from the lower right circle for his second goal of the 
game and third of the playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
Brian Propp made it 4-2 at 6:58, beating Roy from in front for his third goal 
of the playoffs. Roy, the NHL's top regular-season goaltender, was lifted in 
favor of Brian Hayward. 
</P>
<P>
Washington 7, New York Rangers 1 -- John Druce scored eight goals for the 
Capitals in 45 regular-season games, but he continued his offensive binge in 
the playoffs, scoring two goals during a four-goal first period at Landover, 
Md., as the Capitals took a 2-1 lead in the Patrick Division finals. 
</P>
<P>
Druce scored his eighth and ninth goals of the playoffs by twice stuffing in 
his own rebound. He also assisted on Geoff Courtnall's goals in the first and 
third periods. 
</P>
<P>
The Capitals, who took a team playoff-record 49 shots, had their victory 
tempered somewhat by the loss of goalie Don Beaupre, who left the game after 
suffering a groin pull at 3:16 of the first period. His status for the rest of 
the series was not known. 
</P>
</TEXT>
