<HEADLINE>
<P>
SHORT TAKES; 
</P>
<P>
PLEA NAMING MACLAINE REFUSED 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
WASHINGTON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Supreme Court refused to give new life to a copyright lawsuit over actress 
Shirley MacLaine's 1983 best-selling book, "Out on a Limb." 
</P>
<P>
The court, without comment Monday, let stand rulings that MacLaine's book about 
reincarnation and other spiritual subjects did not infringe the copyright of a 
1977 book written by Charles Silva. Silva's suit sought monetary damages from 
MacLaine and the American Broadcasting Companies Inc., which in 1987 made a 
television movie based on the book. Silva, from Peru, authored "Date With the 
Gods" in 1977 and sent a copy to MacLaine. She later discussed it with him and 
eventually traveled with him to areas of Peru described in his book. 
</P>
</TEXT>
